data:
context/background of project; 
Over the last decade one farmhouse in north Austria has hosted countless volunteers and groups seeking to learn how to live in peace with the earth and use her resources carefully, in this case with the focus being on a natural build renovation of the structure.
Out of this learning and the international contacts made in the process has been generated the desire to disseminate skills and methodologies relevant to the creation of a sustainable ecological habitat in which humans may thrive alongside all other species.

objectives of your project; 
Our objective is to instill this profound sense of respect through finishing building the farmhouse together and living in community on the land for a fortnight.

number and profile of participants;
We expect around thirty participants to take part in the build and camp itself, with numbers swelling from the local population when we can open activities up to the public, ie exhibition of achievements, film screenings on ecological issues.
The participants will be young people already developing their changemaker capacities; networked and engaged, interested young people who want to learn and cooperative together.

description of activities;
Our central activities will be a daily programme of natural building workshops; plastering walls with clay and lime, insulating roofs with straw, constructing cob, dry stone- and straw bale- walls, carpentry using hand tools. Complementing this, participants will cook for the group each day using local produce, and in the evenings we will entertain one another holding open mics, cultural performances, and workshops in physical and musical arts like dance and juggling.

methodology to be used in carrying out the project;
The methods used to impart the skills will be collaborative and participatory; founded on the belief that everyone has something to teach and a different way of learning. We will draw heavily from the teaching styles of the cooperative movement, and from contemporary physical education practice.

a short description of the results and impact envisaged;
For participants to understand why building with renewable and natural materials is crucial; how to use them, to enjoy a life living in natural homes and integrated in the landscape, and to teach others how to build them. Other outcomes will be increased capacity in languages and co-working with those from other cultures. Especially for female participants an erosion of the stereotype that building work is 'man's work', or that using power tools is 'the only' modern way to build.
We envisage the impact of this project to resonate throughout the natural build and youth action movements of Europe. For young people to really see the product of their collective labour, for that to have been conducted within a heritage and future-proofing combination framework drawing on the traditions of several countries, we hope will lead to wider capacities, much greater empowerment and increased levels of ambition for those involved.

potential longer term benefits
In the long term, we would like to see this project result in increased international networking, cultural familiarity and exchange within the youth action and sustainable build sectors, and for more women to enter and alter the construction industry. We hope that the attitude of respectful earth care will permeate more strongly throughout our society so that we can halt the degradation of the planets resources. We hope for a skilled, communciative workforce with broad experiences and many languages, to drive our society into ecological equilibrium.
